## Part 4: Direct Field Access Without Full Decode

GridCodec supports **O(1) field access** - you can read individual fields directly from the binary without decoding the entire message. This works because field offsets are known at compile time.

```elixir
Kino.Mermaid.new("""
flowchart LR
    subgraph "Schema-less (JSON, ETF, MessagePack)"
        A[Binary] --> B[Parse ALL fields] --> C[Build map] --> D[Access field]
    end
""")
```

```elixir
Kino.Mermaid.new("""
flowchart LR
    subgraph "Fixed-offset (GridCodec)"
        E[Binary] --> F[Look up offset] --> G[Extract bytes]
    end
""")
```

| Approach     | Time Complexity                       | Memory                                                         |
| ------------ | ------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Schema-less  | O(n) where n = message size           | Allocates map with ALL fields                                  |
| Fixed-offset | O(1) - position known at compile time | Sub-binary reference (shares underlying binary in BEAM's heap) |

### How It Works

GridCodec generates a compile-time offset table:

| Field     | Offset | Size                                |
| --------- | ------ | ----------------------------------- |
| order_id  | 0      | 16                                  |
| user_id   | 16     | 8                                   |
| **price** | **24** | **8** ← `binary_part(msg, 24, 8)` |
| quantity  | 32     | 4                                   |
| ...       | ...    | ...                                 |

**Use cases:**

* **Event routing** - Route by message type without full decode
* **Message filtering** - Skip messages based on header fields
* **Fan-out** - Pass binary to multiple processes, each reads what it needs
* **Logging** - Extract timestamp/ID for logs

### Benchmark: Direct Field Access vs Full Decode

```elixir
# Pre-wrap for direct field access
envelope = Bench.GridCodec.Order.wrap(encodings["GridCodec"])

defmodule Bench.FieldAccess do
  def run(envelope, encodings) do
    Benchee.run(
      %{
        "GridCodec: direct" => fn -> Bench.Functions.get_gridcodec_direct(envelope) end,
        "GridCodec: decode" => fn -> Bench.Functions.get_gridcodec_decode(encodings["GridCodec"]) end,
        "Protobuf: decode" => fn -> Bench.Functions.get_protobuf(encodings["Protobuf"]) end,
        "ETF: decode" => fn -> Bench.Functions.get_etf(encodings["ETF"]) end,
        "JSON: decode" => fn -> Bench.Functions.get_json(encodings["JSON (Jason)"]) end
      },
      time: 3,
      warmup: 1,
      print: [configuration: false, benchmarking: false]
    )
  end
end

field_access_results = Bench.FieldAccess.run(envelope, encodings)

field_data =
  field_access_results.scenarios
  |> Enum.map(fn s ->
    %{
      method: s.name,
      ips: s.run_time_data.statistics.ips,
      ips_millions: Float.round(s.run_time_data.statistics.ips / 1_000_000, 2),
      median_ns: Float.round(s.run_time_data.statistics.median, 1)
    }
  end)
  |> Enum.sort_by(& &1.ips, :desc)

# Calculate speedup
json_ips = Enum.find(field_data, & &1.method =~ "JSON").ips
field_data = Enum.map(field_data, fn row ->
  Map.put(row, :speedup_vs_json, "#{Float.round(row.ips / json_ips, 1)}x")
end)

Kino.DataTable.new(field_data)
```

```elixir
Vl.new(width: 600, height: 300, title: "Single Field Access: Direct vs Full Decode")
|> Vl.data_from_values(field_data)
|> Vl.mark(:bar, corner_radius_end: 4)
|> Vl.encode_field(:y, "method", 
    type: :nominal, 
    sort: [field: "ips", order: "descending"],
    axis: [title: nil, label_font_size: 11])
|> Vl.encode_field(:x, "ips_millions", 
    type: :quantitative, 
    title: "Million operations/second")
|> Vl.encode_field(:color, "method", 
    type: :nominal, 
    legend: nil,
    scale: [scheme: "set2"])
```

## Part 5: Memory Efficiency

Let's visualize memory allocation per operation:

```elixir
memory_data = 
  (encode_data ++ decode_data)
  |> Enum.map(fn row -> 
    %{
      format: row.format,
      operation: if(Enum.member?(encode_data, row), do: "encode", else: "decode"),
      memory_bytes: row.memory_bytes
    }
  end)
  |> Enum.filter(& &1.memory_bytes > 0)

Vl.new(width: 600, height: 400, title: "Memory Allocation per Operation")
|> Vl.data_from_values(memory_data)
|> Vl.mark(:bar)
|> Vl.encode_field(:y, "format", type: :nominal, axis: [title: nil])
|> Vl.encode_field(:x, "memory_bytes", type: :quantitative, title: "Bytes allocated")
|> Vl.encode_field(:color, "operation", type: :nominal)
|> Vl.encode_field(:y_offset, "operation", type: :nominal)
```

## Summary: When to Use What

| Format          | Field Access | Use Case                                |
| --------------- | ------------ | --------------------------------------- |
| **GridCodec**   | O(1) direct  | BEAM-only, schema known at compile time |
| **ElixirProto** | Full decode  | BEAM-only, schema-based binary          |
| **Protobuf**    | Full decode  | Cross-language interop, schema-based    |
| **ETF**         | Full decode  | BEAM native, no schema needed           |
| **MessagePack** | Full decode  | Compact binary, cross-language          |
| **JSON**        | Full decode  | Universal tooling, debugging            |

### GridCodec Requirements

* Schema must be known at compile time
* BEAM/Elixir only (no cross-language support)
* Schema changes require versioning

### When GridCodec Makes Sense

* High message volume where per-message overhead matters
* Need to read individual fields without full decode
* Fan-out scenarios where binary sharing reduces memory
* Internal BEAM services with shared schema
